`,n.jsxs(t.p,{children:["I have been building software for ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"more than ten years"}),'. This post is not a trend piece about "developers in general." It is ',n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"how my days actually felt"})," - the tabs, the fear, the small victories, and the bugs that followed me to bed."]}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.p,{children:["Today I am a ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"software engineer with experience at senior level"}),", based in ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"London"}),", shipping production systems I am proud of: ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"React and Next.js"})," front ends, ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"Node.js"})," APIs and services, and cloud deployments on ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"Azure and AWS"})," with ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"CI/CD"})," pipelines. I have built customer-facing web apps, internal tools, and integrations that had to stay secure and scalable under real traffic - not just tutorials in a sandbox. This article is about the decade of judgment behind that work, not a highlight reel."]}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.p,{children:[n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"What I do today:"})," I design and ship production systems across frontend and backend, review architectural decisions, and help teams move faster without sacrificing quality. I own features ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"end-to-end"})," - from understanding the requirement through implementation, testing, deployment, and follow-up when something misbehaves in the wild."]}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.p,{children:[n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"How I got here:"})," I started with basic frontend features and gradually moved into ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"full-stack development"})," - APIs, databases, cloud deployments, and the unglamorous work of keeping systems running. Over time, my role shifted from solving my own tickets to helping others solve theirs: reviewing code, pairing with colleagues, guiding technical decisions, and pushing for ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"simpler, more maintainable"})," solutions across the team."]}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.p,{children:["If parts of this sound familiar, good. I do not think I was uniquely cursed. I think many of us lived parallel versions of the same career. But the details below are ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"mine"}),"."]}),`
`,n.jsx(t.h2,{children:"My morning, back in the day"}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.p,{children:["I arrive. Coffee. Open laptop. My brain already has a queue of ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"seventeen browser tabs"}),":"]}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.ul,{children:[`
`,n.jsx(t.li,{children:"Stack Overflow (a question from 2009, accepted answer from 2011, closed as duplicate)"}),`
`,n.jsx(t.li,{children:'Google ("javascript remove item from array not working")'}),`
`,n.jsx(t.li,{children:"JSBin - honestly, my real IDE some mornings"}),`
`,n.jsx(t.li,{children:"Regex101 - where I learned that hope has capture groups"}),`
`,n.jsx(t.li,{children:"A GitHub issue titled something unhelpful"}),`
