`,n.jsxs(t.p,{children:["My senior would sit with me. We ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"pair programmed"})," regularly. Colleagues wandered over. We debated ",n.jsx(t.span,{"data-rehype-pretty-code-figure":"",children:n.jsx(t.code,{"data-language":"plaintext","data-theme":"github-dark",children:n.jsx(t.span,{"data-line":"",children:n.jsx(t.span,{children:"var"})})})})," like constitutional law. Someone would casually mention ",n.jsx(t.span,{"data-rehype-pretty-code-figure":"",children:n.jsx(t.code,{"data-language":"plaintext","data-theme":"github-dark",children:n.jsx(t.span,{"data-line":"",children:n.jsx(t.span,{children:"git reset --hard"})})})})," and I would feel my soul leave my body."]}),`
`,n.jsx(t.p,{children:"That was a normal Tuesday for me."}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.p,{children:["Early in my career, I did not split my time evenly between learning and shipping. ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"Most of my week went to learning"}),' - courses on learning platforms, tutorials, blog posts, experiments in sandboxes. A smaller share was code that eventually reached production, often after staging, second-guessing, and a PM asking if we could "just hotfix it."']}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.p,{children:[n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"Even in that learning-heavy phase, I was still contributing."})," I shipped features that reached production, supported live systems real people depended on, and learned under deadline pressure - not in a vacuum. The struggle was real; so was the output."]}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.p,{children:["I also ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"answered questions on Stack Overflow"})," when I could. I had taken so much from that community at 2 a.m.; paying it forward felt like part of the job. I maintained ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"public repositories"})," too - partly portfolio, partly proof to myself that I could finish things."]}),`
`,n.jsx(t.h2,{children:"The impact behind the struggle"}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.p,{children:["The stories below are about ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"how it felt"}),". The outcomes were more concrete:"]}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.ul,{children:[`
`,n.jsxs(t.li,{children:[n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"Customer-facing features"})," people used daily - not demo apps"]}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.li,{children:[n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"Internal tools"})," that reduced manual work and helped teams ship faster"]}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.li,{children:[n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"Production fixes under pressure"})," when something broke and users were waiting"]}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.li,{children:[n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"Performance and reliability improvements"})," on systems that had to handle growing traffic without falling over"]}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.li,{children:[n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"Decisions that reduced risk"})," - tighter reviews, better typing, fewer incidents before merge"]}),`
`]}),`
`,n.jsxs(t.p,{children:["I am not listing employer names or vanity metrics here. But I want to be clear: this was never a decade of only studying. It was a decade of ",n.jsx(t.strong,{children:"building, owning, and improving"})," real software."]}),`
